# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ara-drink
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] An **alcoholic beverage** (also called an **alcoholic drink** or **strong drink**) is any drink that contains alcohol, a central nervous system depressant.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] They are typically divided into three classes: beers, wines, and spirits; with alcohol content typically between 3% and 50%.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The exact amount on which a beverage is considered alcoholic differs by country, with some considering drinks containing less than 0.5% to be non-alcoholic.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] These beverages are primarily consumed for the psychoactive effects that they produce.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Many societies have a distinct drinking culture, in which alcoholic drinks are integrated into parties.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Most countries have laws regulating the production, sale, and consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Some regulations require the labeling of the percentage alcohol content (as ABV or proof) and the use of a warning label.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries ban the consumption of alcoholic drinks, but they are legal in most parts of the world.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The temperance movement advocates against the consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The global alcoholic drink industry exceeded $1.5 trillion in 2017.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is one of the most widely used recreational drugs in the world, and about 33% of all humans currently drink alcohol.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In 2015, among Americans, 86% of adults had consumed alcohol at some point, with 70% drinking it in the last year and 56% in the last month.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Several other animals are affected by alcohol similarly to humans and, once they consume it, will consume it again if given the opportunity; however, humans are the only species known to produce alcoholic drinks intentionally.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a depressant, a class of psychoactive drug that slows down activity in the central nervous system.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In low doses it causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death (an overdose).
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Long-term use can lead to alcoholism, an increased risk of developing several types of cancer, cardiovascular disease, and physical dependence.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is classified as a group 1 carcinogen.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Discovery of late Stone Age jugs suggests that intentionally fermented drinks existed at least as early as the Neolithic period.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The oldest verifiable brewery has been found in a prehistoric burial site in a cave near Haifa in modern-day Israel.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Researchers have found residue of 13,000-year-old beer that they think might have been used for ritual feasts to honor the dead.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The traces of a wheat-and-barley-based alcohol were found in stone mortars carved into the cave floor.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The Carmona Wine Urn is a first century Roman glass urn containing intact wine.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Beer was likely brewed from barley as early as 13,000 years ago in the Middle East.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Pliny the Elder wrote about the *golden age* of winemaking in Rome, the 2nd century BCE (200–100 BCE), when vineyards were planted.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Examination and analysis of ancient pottery jars from the neolithic village of Jiahu in the Henan province of northern China revealed residue left behind by the alcoholic drinks they had once contained.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Chemical analysis of the residue confirmed that a fermented drink made of grape and hawthorn fruit wine, honey mead and rice beer was being produced in 7000–5600 BC.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The residence in which the jar was discovered and other houses in the same village were found to contain many such jars suggesting that wine was an important part of their diet.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The earliest evidence of winemaking was dated at 6,000 to 5,800 BCE in Georgia in the South Caucasus.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Excavations surrounding Neolithic settlements there unearthed grape pips of a variety which differed from those of wild grapes, pointing to deliberate cultivation, and local pottery dated to approximately 6000 BCE was decorated with depictions of celebrating human figures.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The earliest clear chemical evidence of beer produced from barley dates to about 3500–3100 BCE, from the site of Godin Tepe in the Zagros Mountains of western Iran.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] At a site dating to 3100-2900 BCE, a pottery vessel containing residue of alcoholic barley was discovered, possibly serving as the earliest proof of beer brewing in the region.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] However, it is unclear whether it was meant for intoxication or nourishment.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Celtic people were known to have been making types of alcoholic cider as early as 3000 BCE. and wine was consumed in Classical Greece at breakfast or at symposia, and in the 1st century BCE.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Archaeological finds as well as ancient documentation serve as testimony to the popularity and abundance of alcohol in the Sumerian society.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Access to alcohol was regulated, the social elite indulged in it and it served as sacrificial offerings to the gods.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In Sumerian culture Alcohol was also a means for happiness.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In the epic of Gilgamesh, Enkidu the wild man drinks seven jugs of beer, becomes elated and sings with joy.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Other characters routinely drink water, but drink alcohol when celebrating.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] During the new year celebrations, the ceremonial reenactment of the drunken union between the king of Uruk and the high priestess of Ishtar, the goddess of procreation, symbolized the genesis of Ninkasi, the beer goddess.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A hymn to Ninkasi gives a detailed description of hash production in Sumer, involving the fermentation of bread and the addition of grapes and honey, resulting in an unfiltered brew drunk through straws.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In Hierakonpolis, Egypt, the remains of a brewery dating to circa 3400 BCE was unearthed, with an estimated yield of up to 1135 litres (300 US gallons) of brew per day.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Wine was a symbol of power and was imported from abroad, hence it was reserved for royalty and the social elite, while beer was the drink of common society.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In the tomb of the Scorpion king, who ruled Hierakonpolis when the brewery was built, approximately 700 wine jars imported from the southern Levant were unearthed.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Financial documents recorded that the daily ration of beer for the workers who built the pyramids of Giza was nearly 4 litres, and modern reproductions of the ancient recipe produced a brew weighed in at 5 percent ABV, the same as that of the modern day pint.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Despite the many Egyptian sources describing brewing methods, very few discuss intoxication.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In honor of this deed a red coloured alcohol was drunk in large quantities during the festival causing similar intoxicated stupors.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Osiris was also associated with wine, as his death and resurrection were compared to the cycle of withering and regrowth of the vine during the winter and spring.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Multiple amphorae were discovered in the graves of pharaohs and elites as provisions for the afterlife and as offerings to Osiris, commonly with labels detailing their origin, maker, and date.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Over time, labels eventually included assessments of quality as well, such as "good," (*nfr*) "very good," (*nfr nfr*) or "very very good," (*nfr nfr nfr*) alongside provenance, and it was believed that certain vintages improved with age.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Archaeological findings reveal that some wines buried with their owners were several decades old, exceeding the average life expectancy, and therefore assumed to have outlived their creators.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Medieval Muslim chemists such as Jābir ibn Ḥayyān (Latin: Geber, ninth century) and Abū Bakr al-Rāzī (Latin: Rhazes, c.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] 865–925) experimented extensively with the distillation of various substances.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The distillation of wine is attested in Arabic works attributed to al-Kindī (c.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] 872–950), and in the 28th book of al-Zahrāwī's (Latin: Abulcasis, 936–1013) *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf* (later translated into Latin as *Liber servatoris*).
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] 12th century: The process of distillation spread from the Middle East to Italy, where distilled alcoholic drinks were recorded in the mid-12th century.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In Italy, the works of Taddeo Alderotti (1223–1296) describe a method for concentrating alcohol involving repeated fractional distillation through a water-cooled still.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] By the early 14th century, distilled alcoholic drinks had spread throughout the European continent.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Distillation spread to Ireland and Scotland no later than the 15th century, as did the common European practice of distilling "aqua vitae", primarily for medicinal purposes.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking hard liquor was common occurrence in early nineteenth-century United States.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The Whiskey Rebellion (also known as the Whiskey Insurrection) was a violent tax protest in the United States beginning in 1791 and ending in 1794 during the presidency of George Washington.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The so-called "whiskey tax" was the first tax imposed on a domestic product by the newly formed federal government.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Beer was difficult to transport and spoiled more easily than rum and whiskey.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The Rum Rebellion of 1808 was a *coup d'état* in the then-British penal colony of New South Wales, staged by the New South Wales Corps in order to depose Governor William Bligh.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Australia's first and only military coup, its name derives from the illicit rum trade of early Sydney, over which the 'Rum Corps', as it became known, maintained a monopoly.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] During the first half of the 19th century, it was widely referred to in Australia as the Great Rebellion.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The alcohol monopoly system has a long history in various countries, often implemented to limit the availability and consumption of alcohol for public health and social welfare reasons.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The alcohol monopoly was created in the Swedish town of Falun in 1850, to prevent overconsumption and reduce the profit motive for sales of alcohol.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] It later went all over the country in 1905 when the Swedish parliament ordered all sales of vodka to be done via local alcohol monopolies.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In 1894, the Russian Empire established a state monopoly on vodka, which became a major source of revenue for the Russian government.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Beer is a beverage fermented from grain mash.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] It is typically made from barley or a blend of several grains and flavored with hops.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Most beer is naturally carbonated as part of the fermentation process.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] If the fermented mash is distilled, then the drink becomes a spirit.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Beer is the most consumed alcoholic beverage in the world.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Cider or cyder (/ˈsaɪdər/ *SY-dər*) is a fermented alcoholic drink made from any fruit juice; apple juice (traditional and most common), peaches, pears ("Perry" cider) or other fruit.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Cider alcohol content varies from 1.2% ABV to 8.5% or more in traditional English ciders.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In some regions, cider may be called "apple wine".
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is an ethanol-based water solution with approximately 15-17% ABV without sweet reserve.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is exclusively fermented with white sugar, yeast, and water.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is clarified after the fermentation to produce a colorless or off-white liquid with no discernible taste other than that of ethanol.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Mead (/miːd/), also called hydromel, is an alcoholic drink made by fermenting honey with water, sometimes with various fruits, spices, grains, or hops.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The alcoholic content of mead may range from as low as 3% ABV to more than 20%.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The defining characteristic of mead is that the majority of the drink's fermentable sugar is derived from honey.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Pulque is the Mesoamerican fermented drink made from the "honey water" of maguey, *Agave americana*.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Pulque can be distilled to produce tequila or Mezcal.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Rice wine is an alcoholic drink fermented and possibly distilled from rice, consumed in East Asia, Southeast Asia and South Asia.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Sake, huangjiu, mijiu, and cheongju are popular examples of East Asian rice wine.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Wine is a fermented beverage most commonly produced from grapes.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Wine involves a longer fermentation process than beer and often a long aging process (months or years), resulting in an alcohol content of 9%–16% ABV.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Sparkling wines such as French Champagne, Catalan Cava and Italian Prosecco are also made from grapes, with a secondary fermentation.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Fruit wines are made from fruits other than grapes, such as plums, cherries, or apples.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Wine, beer, and spirits are produced through the activity of yeasts, a group of roughly 160 species of single-celled fungi, some of which are beneficial, while others are associated with food spoilage or human disease.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The most commonly used yeasts in fermentation and baking belong to the genus *Saccharomyces*, whose name means "sugar fungus".
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] These organisms are cultivated both for their role in generating flavors and aromas considered desirable, and for their ability to inhibit the growth of competing microbes which would otherwise infect food.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Their production of alcohol is linked to their capacity to function with minimal oxygen.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Distilled beverages (also called liquors or spirit drinks) are alcoholic drinks produced by distilling (i.e., concentrating by distillation) ethanol produced by means of fermenting grain, fruit, or vegetables.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Unsweetened, distilled, alcoholic drinks that have an alcohol content of at least 20% ABV are called *spirits*.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] For the most common distilled drinks, such as whisky (or whiskey) and vodka, the alcohol content is around 40%.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The term *hard liquor* is used in North America to distinguish distilled drinks from undistilled ones (implicitly weaker).
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Brandy, gin, mezcal, rum, tequila, vodka, whisky (or whiskey), baijiu, shōchū and soju are examples of distilled drinks.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Distilling concentrates the alcohol and eliminates some of the congeners.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Freeze distillation concentrates ethanol along with methanol and fusel alcohols (fermentation by-products partially removed by distillation) in applejack.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine is wine, such as port or sherry, to which a distilled beverage (usually brandy) has been added.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine is distinguished from spirits made from wine in that spirits are produced by means of distillation, while fortified wine is wine that has had a spirit added to it.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Many different styles of fortified wine have been developed, including port, sherry, madeira, marsala, commandaria, and the aromatized wine vermouth.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit, also called "neutral grain spirit", is alcohol which has been purified by means of "rectification" (i.e. repeated distillation).
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The term *neutral* refers to the spirit's lack of flavor that would have been present if the mash ingredients had been distilled to a lower level of alcoholic purity.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit also lacks any flavoring added to it after distillation (as is done, for example, with gin).
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Other kinds of spirits, such as whiskey, (or whisky) are distilled to a lower alcohol percentage to preserve the flavor of the mash.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit is a clear, colorless, flammable liquid that may contain as much as 95% ABV.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] It is often used for medicinal purposes.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] It may be a grain spirit, or it may be made from other plants.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] It is used in mixed drinks, liqueurs, and tinctures, and also as a household solvent.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In the alcoholic drinks industry, congeners are substances produced during fermentation.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] These substances include small amounts of chemicals such as occasionally desired alcohols, like propanol and 3-methyl-1-butanol, as well as compounds that are never desired such as acetone, acetaldehyde and glycols.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Congeners are responsible for most of the taste and aroma of distilled alcoholic drinks and contribute to the taste of non-distilled drinks.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] It has been suggested that these substances contribute to the symptoms of a hangover.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Tannins are congeners found in wine in the presence of phenolic compounds.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tannins add bitterness, have a drying sensation, taste herbaceous, and are often described as astringent.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tannins add balance, complexity, structure and make a wine last longer, so they play an important role in the aging of wine.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Top-shelf liquor (or "premium liquor") is a term used in marketing to describe higher-priced alcoholic beverages, typically stored on the top shelves within bars.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A mixed drink is a beverage in which two or more ingredients are mixed, and is often alcoholic.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol powder or powdered alcohol or dry alcohol is a product generally made using micro-encapsulation.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] When reconstituted with water, the powder becomes an alcoholic drink.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A well drink or rail drink is an alcoholic beverage or mixed drink made using the lower-cost liquors stored within easy reach of the bartender in the bar's "speed rail", "speed rack", or "well", a rack or shelf at a lower level than the bar that the bartender uses to prepare drinks.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The average number of people who drink as of 2016 was 39% for males and 25% for females (2.4 billion people in total).
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Females on average drink 0.7 drinks per day while males drink 1.7 drinks per day.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The rates of drinking varies significantly in different areas of the world.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking games are games which involve the consumption of alcoholic beverages and often enduring the subsequent intoxication resulting from them.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Evidence of the existence of drinking games dates back to antiquity.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking games have been banned at some institutions, particularly colleges and universities.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A drinking song is a song sung while drinking an alcoholic beverage.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A beer garden (German: *Biergarten*) is an outdoor area in which beer and food are served, typically at shared tables shaded by trees.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A beer hall (German: *Bierpalast, Bierhalle*) is a large pub that specializes in beer.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A cider house is an establishment that sells alcoholic cider for consumption on the premises.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Some cider houses also sell cider "to go", for consumption off the premises.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A traditional cider house was often little more than a room in a farmhouse or cottage, selling locally fermented cider.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] An ouzeri (Greek *ουζερί* IPA: [uzeˈri]) is a type of Greek tavern which serves ouzo (a Greek liquor) and mezedes (small finger foods).
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Pulquerías (or pulcherías) are a type of tavern in Mexico that specialize in serving an alcoholic beverage known as pulque.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A tiki bar is a themed drinking establishment that serves elaborate cocktails, especially rum-based mixed drinks such as the Mai Tai and Zombie cocktails.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Tiki bars are aesthetically defined by their tiki culture décor which is based upon a romanticized conception of tropical cultures, most commonly Polynesian.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A toddy shop is a drinking establishment seen in some parts of India (particularly Kerala) where palm toddy, a mildly alcoholic beverage made from the sap of palm trees, is served along with food.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A wine bar is a tavern-like business focusing on selling wine, rather than liquor or beer.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A typical feature of many wine bars is a wide selection of wines available by the glass.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Some wine bars are profiled on wines of a certain type of origin, such as Italian wine or Champagne.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] While many wine bars are private "stand-alone" establishments, in some cases, wine bars are associated with a specific wine retailer or other outlet of wine, to provide additional marketing for that retailer's wine portfolio.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In countries where licensing regulations allow this, some wine bars also sell the wines they serve, and effectively function as a hybrid between a wine shop and a wine bar.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A beer festival is an event at which a variety of beers are available for purchase.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] There may be a theme, for instance beers from a particular area, or a particular brewing style such as winter ales.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Annual wine festivals celebrate viticulture and usually occur after the harvest of the grapes which, in the northern hemisphere, generally falls at the end of September and runs until well into October or later.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] They are common in most wine regions around the world and are to be considered in the tradition of other harvest festivals.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Beer tasting is a way to learn more about the history, ingredients, and production of beer, as well as different beer styles, hops, yeast, and beer presentation.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A common approach is to analyze the appearance, smell, and taste of the beer, and then make a final judgment on the beer's quality.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] There are various scales used by beer journalists and experts to rate beer, such as the 1-20 scale used by British sommelier Jancis Robinson and the 1-100 scale used by American sommelier Joshua M.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Professional organizations like the Wine & Spirit Education Trust often rate beer using verbal grades ranging from "faulty" to "outstanding" on a 1-5 scale.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tasting, on the other hand, is the sensory examination and evaluation of wine.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] While the practice of wine tasting is ancient, a more formalized methodology has been established since the 14th century.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Modern, professional wine tasters use specialized terminology to describe the range of perceived flavors, aromas, and general characteristics of a wine.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] More informal, recreational tasting may involve similar terminology, but with a less analytical process and a more general, personal appreciation of the wine.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Craft beer tourism refers to tourism where the primary motivation of travel is to visit a brewery, beer festival, beer related activity or other event that allows attendees to experience all aspects of the craft beer-making, consuming and purchasing process.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Enotourism, oenotourism, wine tourism, or **vinitourism** refers to tourism whose purpose is or includes the tasting, consumption or purchase of wine, often at or near the source.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Where other types of tourism are often passive in nature, enotourism can consist of visits to wineries, tasting wines, vineyard walks, or even taking an active part in the harvest.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] An apéritif is any alcoholic beverage usually served before a meal to stimulate the appetite, while a digestif is any alcoholic beverage served after a meal for the stated purpose of improving digestion.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine, liqueurs, and dry champagne are common apéritifs.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Because apéritifs are served before dining, they are usually dry rather than sweet.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] One example is Cinzano, a brand of vermouth.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Digestifs include brandy, fortified wines and herb-infused spirits (Drambuie).
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Pure ethanol tastes bitter to humans; some people also describe it as sweet.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] However, ethanol is also a moderately effective solvent for many fatty substances and essential oils.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] This facilitates the use of flavoring and coloring compounds in alcoholic drinks as a taste mask, especially in distilled drinks.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Some flavors may be naturally present in the beverage's raw material.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Beer and wine may also be flavored before fermentation, and spirits may be flavored before, during, or after distillation.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Sometimes flavor is obtained by allowing the beverage to stand for months or years in oak barrels, usually made of American or French oak.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A few brands of spirits may also have fruit or herbs inserted into the bottle at the time of bottling.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Wine is important in cuisine not just for its value as an accompanying beverage, but as a flavor agent, primarily in stocks and braising, since its acidity lends balance to rich savory or sweet dishes.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Wine sauce is an example of a culinary sauce that uses wine as a primary ingredient.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Natural wines may exhibit a broad range of alcohol content, from below 9% to above 16% ABV, with most wines being in the 12.5–14.5% range.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wines (usually with brandy) may contain 20% alcohol or more.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Vinegar (*vyn egre*; sour wine) is an aqueous solution of acetic acid and trace compounds that may include flavorings.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Vinegar typically contains from 5% to 18% acetic acid by volume.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Usually, the acetic acid is produced by a double fermentation, converting simple sugars to ethanol using yeast and ethanol to acetic acid using acetic acid bacteria.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Wine and food matching is the process of pairing food dishes with wine to enhance the dining experience.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In many cultures, wine has had a long history of being a staple at the dinner table and in some ways both the winemaking and culinary traditions of a region will have evolved together over the years.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Rather than following a set of rules, local cuisines were paired simply with local wines.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The modern "art" of food pairings is a relatively recent phenomenon, fostering an industry of books and media with guidelines for pairings of particular foods and wine.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In the restaurant industry, sommeliers are often present to make food pairing recommendations for the guest.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The main concept behind pairings is that certain elements (such as texture and flavor) in both food and wine interact with each other, and thus finding the right combination of these elements will make the entire dining experience more enjoyable.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] However, taste and enjoyment are very subjective and what may be a "textbook perfect" pairing for one taster could be less enjoyable to another.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Alcoholic beverages are typical offerings for the folk saint Maximón, and Santa Muerte.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Both folk saints have been described as narco-saints.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A libation is a ritual pouring of a liquid, or grains such as rice, as an offering to a deity or spirit, or in memory of the dead.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] It was common in many religions of antiquity and continues to be offered in cultures today.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Wine or other alcoholic drinks are often used for libation.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Libation was part of ancient Egyptian society where it was a drink offering to honor and please the various divinities, sacred ancestors, humans present and humans who are alive but not physically present, as well as the environment.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] It is suggested that libation originated somewhere in the upper Nile Valley and spread out to other regions of Africa and the world.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In the Quechua and Aymara cultures of the South American Andes, it is common to pour a small amount of one's beverage on the ground before drinking as an offering to the Pachamama, or Mother Earth.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] This especially holds true when drinking Chicha, an alcoholic beverage unique to this part of the world.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The libation ritual is commonly called *challa* and is performed quite often, usually before meals and during celebrations.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The amount of sacramental wine consumed during the Eucharist is typically limited to a single sip or small portion, which does not result in a measurable increase in the participant's blood alcohol content.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] This controlled and symbolic consumption of the sacramental wine is an integral part of the Eucharistic rite and does not lead to intoxication.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] According to the Catholic Church, the sacramental wine used in the Eucharist must contain alcohol.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Some Evangelical Lutheran Church in America (ELCA) congregations make grape juice available for children and those who are abstaining from alcohol and some will accommodate those with an allergy to wheat, gluten, or grapes.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A tincture is typically an extract of plant or animal material dissolved in ethanol (ethyl alcohol).
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Solvent concentrations of 25–60% are common, but may run as high as 90%.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In chemistry, a tincture is a solution that has ethanol as its solvent.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In herbal medicine, alcoholic tinctures are made with various ethanol concentrations, which should be at least 20% alcohol for preservation purposes.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A flaming drink is often ignited for aesthetic and entertainment purposes.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Alcoholic beverage may be consumed to celebrate observances such as the International Beer Day, International whisk(e)y day, or National Vodka Day.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] They also drink them for social events like International Women's Collaboration Brew Day, where people come together to make beer.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol measurements are units of measurement for determining amounts of beverage alcohol.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol concentration in beverages is commonly expressed as alcohol by volume (ABV), ranging from less than 0.1% in fruit juices to up to 98% in rare cases of spirits.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A standard drink is used globally to quantify alcohol intake, though its definition varies widely by country.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Serving sizes of alcoholic beverages also vary by country.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol laws regulate the manufacture, packaging, labelling, distribution, sale, consumption, blood alcohol content of motor vehicle drivers, open containers, and transportation of alcoholic drinks.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Such laws generally seek to reduce the adverse health and social impacts of alcohol consumption.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In particular, alcohol laws set the legal drinking age, which usually varies between 15 and 21 years old, sometimes depending upon the type of alcoholic drink (e.g., beer vs wine vs hard liquor or distillates).
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries do not have a legal drinking or purchasing age, but most countries set the minimum age at 18 years.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries, such as the U.S., have the drinking age higher than the legal age of majority (18), at age 21 in all 50 states.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Such laws may take the form of permitting distribution only to licensed stores, monopoly stores, or pubs and they are often combined with taxation, which serves to reduce the demand for alcohol (by raising its price) and it is a form of revenue for governments.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] These laws also often limit the hours or days (e.g., "blue laws") on which alcohol may be sold or served, as can also be seen in the "last call" ritual in US and Canadian bars, where bartenders and servers ask patrons to place their last orders for alcohol, due to serving hour cutoff laws.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In some countries, alcohol cannot be sold to a person who is already intoxicated.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol laws in many countries prohibit drunk driving.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In some jurisdictions, alcoholic drinks are totally prohibited for reasons of religion (e.g., Islamic countries with sharia law) or for reasons of local option, public health, and morals (e.g., Prohibition in the United States from 1920 to 1933).
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In jurisdictions which enforce sharia law, the consumption of alcoholic drinks is an illegal offense, although such laws may exempt non-Muslims.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is used in rum-running, the illegal business of smuggling alcoholic beverages where such transportation is forbidden by law.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Wine fraud relates to the commercial aspects of wine.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The most prevalent type of fraud is one where wines are adulterated, usually with the addition of cheaper products (e.g. juices) and sometimes with harmful chemicals and sweeteners (compensating for color or flavor).
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Moonshine is illegal to produce and sell in most countries.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In Prohibition-era United States, moonshine distillation was done at night to deter discovery.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Once the liquor was distilled, drivers called "runners" or "bootleggers" smuggled moonshine liquor across the region in cars specially modified for speed and load-carrying capacity.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Outbreaks of methanol poisoning have occurred when methanol is used to adulterate moonshine.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In Australia, a sly-grog shop (or shanty) is an unlicensed hotel, liquor-store or other vendor of alcoholic beverages, sometimes with the added connotation of selling poor-quality products.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Pruno also known as prison hooch or prison wine, is a term used in the United States to describe an improvised alcoholic beverage.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] It is variously made from apples, oranges, fruit cocktail, fruit juices, hard candy, sugar, high fructose syrup, and possibly other ingredients, including crumbled bread.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Most countries have laws specifically for the offense of drunk driving.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Driving under the influence (DUI) or driving while intoxicated (DWI), is the crime of driving a motor vehicle while impaired by alcohol or other drugs (including those prescribed by physicians).
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Public intoxication laws vary widely by jurisdiction, but include public nuisance laws, open-container laws, and prohibitions on drinking alcohol in public or certain areas.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a common metabolic by-product formed during the breakdown of sugars in many living cells, though it is typically further metabolised to release additional energy.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Certain yeasts constitute an exception, as they excrete alcohol into their environment, where it acts as a chemical defense against competing microorganisms; this role is analogous to that of lactic acid in fermented foods and aromatic compounds in plants.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] While advantageous to yeast, alcohol is toxic to most cells, and in humans its intoxicating effects result from interference with the normal functioning of brain cells.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a depressant, which in low doses causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] A meta analysis of 107 cohort studies concludes low daily alcohol intake provides no health benefits and increased consumption, even at relatively low levels of daily intake (>2 beverages for women and >3 beverages for men), increases health- and mortality-risks.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Short-term effects of alcohol consumption range from a decrease in anxiety and motor skills and euphoria at lower doses to intoxication (drunkenness), to stupor, unconsciousness, anterograde amnesia (memory "blackouts"), and central nervous system depression at higher doses.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Cell membranes are highly permeable to alcohol, so once it is in the bloodstream, it can diffuse into nearly every cell in the body.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol can greatly exacerbate sleep problems.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] During abstinence, residual disruptions in sleep regularity and sleep patterns are the greatest predictors of relapse.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Long-term use can lead to an alcohol use disorder, an increased risk of developing physical dependence, cardiovascular disease, and several types of cancer.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Some nations have introduced alcohol packaging warning messages that inform consumers about alcohol and cancer, as well as fetal alcohol syndrome.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] The addition of warning labels on alcoholic beverages is historically supported by organizations of the temperance movement, such as the Woman's Christian Temperance Union, as well as by medical organisations, such as the Irish Cancer Society.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] WHO estimates nearly half of alcohol-attributable cancers in the WHO European Region are linked to light or moderate drinking defined as "less than 1.5 litres of wine or less than 3.5 litres of beer or less than 450 millilitres of spirits per week".
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Public awareness of the link between alcohol consumption and cancer is low in the U.S.
[src:ara-drink/alcoholic-beverage] Surgeon General argued for the use of cancer warning labels on alcohol products.
[src:ara-drink/amazake] There are several recipes for *amazake* that have been used for hundreds of years.
[src:ara-drink/amazake] By a popular recipe, *kōji* is added to cooled whole grain rice causing enzymes to break down the carbohydrates into simpler unrefined sugars.
[src:ara-drink/amazake] As the mixture incubates, sweetness develops naturally.
[src:ara-drink/amazake] By another recipe, sake kasu is mixed with water and sugar is added.
[src:ara-drink/amazake] Similar beverages include the Chinese *jiuniang* which is more pudding like and Korean *gamju* or *sikhye*.
[src:ara-drink/amazake] In grape winemaking, must – sweet, thick, unfermented grape juice – is a similar product.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] Today, the rice wine for distilled soju is usually fermented for about 15 days.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] The process of making the fermentation starter (*nuruk*) for Andong soju consists of washing and drying wheat, which is then crushed and mixed with water.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] After, it is filtered, fermented, mixed with hard-boiled rice, and placed in a jug with water for about 15 days.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] The aged liquor is then boiled in a *sot* (cauldron).
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] A *soju gori* (two-storied distilling appliance with a pipe), and a cooling device are placed on the *sot*, and flour dough is used to make an air-tight seal.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] It is spread on the gap between the *soju gori* and the cooling device so that no steam escapes.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] When the aged liquor is heated, it vaporizes, and the vaporized steam is cooled by the cold water in the upper parts of the *soju gori*.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] This causes the vaporized alcohol to be condensed and trickle down through the pipe.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] The development of soju in Andong is related to the Yuan dynasty's movement into the Korean Peninsula during the 13th century.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] The Yuan dynasty's supply base was in Andong and was established to prepare for an expedition to Japan.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] Andong soju dates back to the Silla dynasty (668–935 AD).
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] The distillation skill was developed by alchemists engaged in trade with Arab tribes.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] Evidence of relations between the Silla and tribes of the Arabian Peninsula includes warrior statues with nonlocal features and Persian glass found at Goereung (hangul: 괘릉; an ancient tomb of Silla in Gyeongju, Gyeongsangbuk-do).
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] China had been drinking hard liquor since the Tang dynasty.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] With the close relationship between Silla and the Tang dynasty, it can be assumed that strong liquor was used in Korea since the Silla period.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] The artisans of Andong soju are Jo Ok-hwa (조옥화; 趙玉花) and Park Jae-seo (박재서; 朴栽緖).
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] These artisans keep alive the traditional ways of making Andong soju through the Korean government's support for discovering traditional alcoholic beverages since the 1986 Asian Games and 1988 Summer Olympics.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] After the Silla period, the skills of making Andong soju were passed down in Andong.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] Jo Ok-hwa made and preserved this Andong soju, so she was designated as "Korean food grand master No.20" on September 18, 2000.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] Daughter-in-law Bae Kyong-hwa (배경화) and son Kim Yeon-park (김연박) continue the tradition.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] Park Jae-seo is a descendant of Pak Eung-ju (박응주), the originator of the Bannam Park clan.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] For preserving his family's tradition, Park Jae-seo was designated as "Korean food grand master No.6" in July 1995.
[src:ara-drink/andong-soju] Andong soju is the only specialty to have two Korean food grandmasters because Jo Ok-hwa and Park Jae-seo's way of making it and materials are different from each other.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Many tribal communities of Arunachal Pradesh use apo during their respective festivals, such as nyokum.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The tribal people offer the drink, every time they drink it, to the uiyu (spirits) by letting a few drops of it fall on the ground.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Other occasions when Apo is served include annually organized ancestor worship ceremonies, the festivals of Ali aye ligang, Nyokum, Dree, and others, and annual agricultural programs.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Apo is known in different names across different tribes in North-Eastern India, such as haaz (Ahom), apong (Mising), zou (zu mai) (Bodo) and Sujen (Deori).
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Apo is not distributed in shops, as apo forms part of a tradition and culture, the apo is shared through generations like a piece of cultural knowledge.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Apos are commonly brewed in households and often served along with rice and chutney as well, irrespective of gender or age differences.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The origins of the apo tradition in the North-Eastern regions are not recorded, However, the tradition may date back to Neolithic period.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Similarly, the word Apo is not a general term for a rice-based drink, as each tribe identifies the drink with different names.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] However, it is believed that the traditional rice beer was first developed by the 'Mising people in Assam.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Thus the etymology of the word refers to its Mising language origins.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Across the different tribes, the brewing method has certain differences, but the substrates used for fermentation are the same.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] This indicates a common ancestor to the brewing culture in North-Eastern India.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Traditionally, two kinds of Apo are being brewed in these regions known as Po:ro Apong and Nogin Apong.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The starter cakes called épob are made out of crushed rice and medicinal plants are used to make the health quotient.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] These starter cakes are one of the most important elements of the rice beers made in the North-Eastern region, including Apo.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] This also refers to the idea of sacredness associated with the Apo making across different tribes as it is not made on an everyday basis, but only for ceremonies, festivals, marriage, and group gatherings.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] In this regard, historically and culturally, the Apo remains as an element of identity in these regions.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Apo is known in different traditional names based on the respective tribes.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Apo is believed to be first developed by the Mising people in Assam.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The term Apo is derived from the traditional name "Apong" in the Mising language.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The Mising community is generally known for its passion for traditional cooking methods and food items.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The cooking method of the Apo is also believed to be shared by the ancestors of Mising community and later spread throughout the tribes in North East India.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Apo is commonly produced in households of northeastern states of Arunachal Pradesh and Assam in India.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Although distinctive methods for brewing exist across the North-Eastern region of India, the process of fermentation remains the same across these regions, indicating common origins of brewing.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] As a first step, the rice collected for making beverage is cooked and then mixed with ash from burnt paddy sticks, which makes the mixture black.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Once the rice is cooked, it is mixed with the fermenting ingredient E-Pob made out of rice and medicinal plants.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Time is taken for the formation of ration changes along with the climate and temperature.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] During summer, the fermentation took 5–6 days.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The fermented mixture is filtered and finally poured into bamboo shoots.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] During these processes, around 30 medicinal plants use to the beverage along with rice.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] This includes leaves, creepers, and grass.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The total period taken for the production of Apo beer is more than 3 months.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Although the alcohol content on the Apo is 18-25% it is more intoxicating in nature.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Recent studies indicate the Apo Beer can be economically benefiting the community as the beer provides the entrepreneurial potential to the community as the rice beer produced in Northeast regions, including Apo are high quality in nature.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The starter cake is one of the most indispensable elements of the Apo beer production process.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The Apo beer produced by the Mising community is identified to have various medicinal and therapeutic properties as a result often used during the preparation of starter cake known as épob.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The beer-making process in each tribe varies according to the environmental factors and other socio-cultural practices associated with the individual tribes.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] These factors are essential in determining the colour, flavour, and sweetness of the flower.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] One major process during the production of Apong is the use of starter cake, i.e. épob which has significant medicinal qualities.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] This quality is of starter cake is determined by the medicinal plants used during the production along with the sanitary conditions used while making the beer.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The making of épob in this regard include the process of collecting a variety of medicinal plant leaves.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The leaves collected are dried placing it on a bamboo mat known as époh after cleaning it.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Fresh leaves can also be used for making the starter cake for making the beer.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The leaves are later ground separately using a wooden tool hand mixer together to make an épob in the shape of oval-shaped balls from the dough made from the mixture.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The folk medicine beliefs of the starter cake derive from the use of local herbs.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Tribes believe that the combination of herbs makes Apo beer an effective agent against various minor diseases.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Most of the plants used for the preparation of the beer are indigenous.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The varieties of Apo beer in the northeast region of India include methods of infusion and decoction used by the local peoples.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Apo is an important element in the socio-cultural aspect of the Mising people.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] The Apo beer is served during religious festivals and ceremonies in Assam such as Marriages, death ceremonies, Ali A:yé Lígang, Porag, and other major community gatherings and celebration.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Apong is usually served along with pork and Purang apin in festivals like Ali A:yé Lígang.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] In local markets, Apo beer is a source of income and livelihood for many families, and contributes to community development.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] In Assam, it has been reportedly found to be sold by local brewers in small bottles.
[src:ara-drink/apo-drink] Apo was featured in the Indian Amazon Prime Video web series *The Family Man* (season 3), where it is depicted as a traditional rice-based alcoholic beverage consumed in Northeast India.
[src:ara-drink/ara-drink] Ara is most commonly made from rice or maize at private homes or farms.
[src:ara-drink/ara-drink] Ara may be either fermented or distilled, and in Bhutan is only legally produced and consumed privately.
[src:ara-drink/ara-drink] Ara production is unregulated in both method and quality, and its sale is prohibited in Bhutan.
[src:ara-drink/ara-drink] Previously, private individuals sold ara through shopkeepers despite the prohibition and faced a harsh government crackdown.
[src:ara-drink/ara-drink] However, because Ara returns far more profit than other forms of maize, many Bhutanese farmers have pressed for legal reform.
[src:ara-drink/ara-drink] The Bhutanese government, meanwhile, is intent on discouraging excessive alcohol consumption, abuse, and associated diseases through taxation and regulation.
[src:ara-drink/ara-drink] Ara is also produced for religious purposes, especially in eastern Bhutan, where it serves as a Lhasoel offering on certain auspicious days.
[src:ara-drink/ara-drink] Ara is also believed to chemically ward off snakes, and is sometimes carried by children for protection.
[src:ara-drink/ara-drink] Through government efforts to reduce ara production and consumption in Lhuntse District, eastern Bhutan, locals conceded something should be done to curb the distinctly eastern Bhutanese tradition of heavy drinking.
[src:ara-drink/ara-drink] The government's strategy is to reduce ara production and consumption gradually until it is eliminated.
[src:ara-drink/ara-drink] Alcoholism and ara production have been notable topics of political discussion Bhutan, especially at the local level.
[src:ara-drink/ara-drink] It may be served neat, with smooth additives like butter and poached egg, or with chunky additives like scrambled egg and rice.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Arak is traditionally made of grapes and aniseed (the seeds of the anise plant); when crushed, their oil provides arak with a slight licorice taste.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Dates, figs, and other fruits are sometimes added.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Typically, arak is a minimum of 50% alcohol by volume (ABV), and can be up to 70% ABV (140 proof).
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The word *arak* comes from Arabic **ʿaraq** (عرق), meaning 'perspiration' or 'sweat', but also 'distillate'.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Its pronunciation varies depending on the regional varieties of Arabic, e.g.: [ˈʕæræʔ] or [ˈʕæræɡ].
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Arak is the name for distilled spirits made in the Middle East from a base of grapes or pomace with anise.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] These are distinct from arrack, derived from same word, but referring to spirits made in southern and southeastern Asia from distilled wines of various other bases.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Arab/Persian and Islamic alchemists, like Jabir Ibn Hayyan, experimented to produce distilled alcohol for medicinal purposes.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Alcohol (*al-kuhl*) and alembic (*al-inbiq*) are Arabic loanwords to several languages, as a result of the success of these experiments, though the invention and use of alcohol long predates distillation.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The first to record a recipe for a distilled spirit (ethanol) was Al-Razi in the 10th century, and the distillate he made was called *arak* and was intended for use as an antiseptic and medical solvent.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] While extracted from grapes (and also dates and grains), it had a much higher alcohol content than wine.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Despite prohibitions against the imbibing of alcohol in Islam, as the use of the spirit and distillation method spread throughout the Islamic world, it was also used recreationally.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The 1936 book *Arbeit und Sitte in Palaestina* ("Work and Customs in Palestine") by German orientalist Gustaf Dalman described a preparation method for arak that uses grapes and anise seeds which he learned in the Galilee region.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Arak is a traditional alcoholic beverage of the Levant and Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] It is distilled and consumed across a wide area in the Middle East, including in Lebanon, Syria, Jordan, Egypt, Iraq, Palestine and Israel.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Sudan, Iran, Morocco, and Greece are also generally recognized as major producers and exporters of Arak.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Arak is a stronger flavored liquor and is usually mixed in proportions of approximately one part arak to two parts water in a traditional Eastern Mediterranean water vessel called an *ibrik* (Arabic: إبريق **ibrīq**), from Middle Persian or Parthian **ābrēz*.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The mixture is then poured into ice-filled cups, usually small, but can also be consumed in regular sized cups.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] This dilution causes the clear liquor to turn a translucent milky-white color; this is because anethole, the essential oil of anise, is soluble in alcohol but not in water.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] This results in an emulsion whose fine droplets scatter the light and turn the liquid translucent, a phenomenon known as the ouzo effect.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Arak is often served with meze, which may include dozens of small traditional dishes, as well as with grilled meat.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] It is also commonly served as an apéritif.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Arak is often called the national drink of Lebanon.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Largely made from the Marawi and Obaideh grape varieties, a center of production is the Bekaa Valley, particularly the Kefraya, Ksara, Domaine des Tourelles, and Massaya vineyards.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Zahlé, where Arak Zahlawi is produced, is considered a capital of arak.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The water used in the production of Arak Zahlawi is traditionally drawn from the Berdawni River.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Before the outbreak of the Syrian Civil War in 2011, production was dominated by two state-run firms, Al-Rayan (based in the city of Sweida) and Al-Mimas (based in a Christian settlement near Homs).
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Together, the two companies held about 85% of Syria's market share in arak.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Since the civil war, however, the companies' profits and the price of arak have declined, with their combined market share falling to under half.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Low-quality counterfeits also proliferated, using pure alcohol (rather than fermented grapes) and an aniseed substitute (rather than real aniseed).
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Iraq formerly manufactured arak, including in Bashiqa in northern Iraq, but most arak production facilities shut down in the 2010s.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Arak is distilled and consumed by Iraq's Yazidi and Christian minorities, although many members of these groups fled after ISIL seized control of large portions of northern Iraq in 2014.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Amid a rise in Islamic conservatism, the Iraqi parliament passed a ban on the importing, manufacturing, and sale of alcoholic beverages in 2016, prompting protests from Iraqi non-Muslims and rights activists.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The ban was not enforced until it was officially gazetted in 2023, triggering border crackdowns.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The ban is not enforced in Iraq's autonomous Kurdistan Region.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] During the age of austerity in the early years of the State of Israel, arak (in Hebrew, ערק) was locally made, with few imports.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The core market for arak was among older, working-class Israelis, and the drink was not favored among younger and modern Israelis.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] In the first two decades of the 21st century, however, arak had a resurgence in popularity.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Arak also continues to be popular among Moroccan Jews in Israel, some of whom regard arak as having folk medicine properties.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Israeli tax reforms in 2013 substantially increased the alcohol tax, and this led to consolidation of the arak market.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The most popular producer is Joseph Gold & Sons, a winery established in 1824 in Haifa by the Gold family, which formerly made vodka in Ukraine before establishing an arak distillery in Israel.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The winery, having moved later to Tirat Carmel outside Haifa, produces different arak brands, including Elite Arak, Alouf Arak, and Amir Arak.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Other major arak producers include Barkan Wine Cellars (which produces Arak Ashkelon) and Kawar Distillery (which produces Arak Kawar, Arak Yuda, and Arak Noah).
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] After the Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon in 2000, some former South Lebanon Army members who settled in Israel began to produce arak using Lebanese (Zahlé) methods.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Arak is locally produced by Palestinian Christians.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The West Bank city of Ramallah is a center of arak distillation.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Imports of arak from Palestine to the U.S. increased after imports of Syrian arak were disrupted by the Syrian civil war.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Several arak brands are produced outside of the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The Arak Carmel brand is produced in Spain, while the Arak Julenar brand is produced by an Iraqi in Greece.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Arak was once produced in Iran, until it was banned following the 1979 Iranian Revolution.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Iranian Armenians locally manufacture black-market arak in Iran, and some foreign brands are also smuggled in the country.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] A locally made Iranian arak moonshine, *aragh sagi*, is made from fermented raisins; in 2020 it sold on the black market for about US$10 for 1.5 liters.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The Persian Empire Distillery, established in 2006 by a Shiraz-born Persian Canadian entrepreneur, distills an arak brand, Arak Saggi, at its distillery in Peterborough, Ontario.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Arak has achieved popularity among consumers in the North Caucasus area of Russia.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Similar aperitifs include the Turkish rakı, the Greek ouzo and tsikoudia, the Italian sambuca and anisette, the Bulgarian and Macedonian mastika, and the Spanish anís.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] However, it is unrelated to the similarly named arrack, a sugarcane-based Indonesian liquor.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Manufacturing begins with the vineyards, and quality grapevines are the key to making good arak.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The vines should be very mature and usually of a golden color.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Instead of being irrigated, the vineyards are left to the care of the Mediterranean climate and make use of the natural rain and sun.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The grapes, which are harvested in late September and early October, are crushed and put in barrels together with the juice (in Arabic *el romeli*) and left to ferment for three weeks.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Occasionally the whole mix is stirred to release the CO2.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Both pot stills and column stills are used.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Stills are usually made of stainless steel or copper.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] Copper stills with a Moorish shape are the most sought after.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The alcohol collected in the first distillation undergoes a second distillation, but this time it is mixed with aniseed.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The ratio of alcohol to aniseed may vary and it is one of the major factors in the quality of the final product.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The finished product is produced during a final distillation which takes place at the lowest possible temperature.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] For a quality arak, the finished spirit is then aged in clay amphoras to allow the angels' share to evaporate.
[src:ara-drink/arak-drink] The liquid remaining after this step is the most suitable for consumption.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] It shares international borders with Bhutan in the west, Myanmar in the east, and a disputed 1,129 km border with China's Tibet Autonomous Region in the north at the McMahon Line.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Nearly four-fifths of Arunachal Pradesh is claimed by China as Southern Tibet as part of the Tibet Autonomous Region; China occupied some regions of Arunachal Pradesh in 1962 but later withdrew its forces.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] As per the 2011 census, Arunachal Pradesh has a population of 1,383,727.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] With only 17 inhabitants per square kilometre, it is the least densely populated state in India.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] It is an ethnically diverse state, with predominantly Monpa people in the west, Tani people in the centre, Mishmi and Tai people in the east, and Naga people in the southeast of the state.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] About 23 major tribes and 100 sub-tribes live in the state, including Nocte, Adi, Nyishi, Singpho, Galo, Tagin, and Apatani.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Nyishi are the largest ethnic group in the region.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Mishmi tribe has three sub-tribes, namely Idu-Mishmi, Digaru-Mishmi, and Miju-Mishmi.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Arunachal Pradesh means *Land of the Dawn-Lit Mountains*, which is the sobriquet for the state in Sanskrit.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The term was coined during the formation of the state.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Prior to the year 1972, it was called North-East Frontier Agency.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The People's Republic of China (PRC) does not recognise Arunachal Pradesh, and claims the land to be part of Tibet, calling it Southern Tibet (Chinese: 藏南 pinyin: *Zàngnán*).
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In ancient Tibetan texts, eastern Arunachal Pradesh and some parts of Tibet were called Lhoyü while the residents were called Lhobha people, while Tawang district and West Kameng district in western Arunachal Pradesh were called Monyul.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Very little ancient history is known about the region apart from the Northwestern corner, and the areas bordering current Assam.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Northwestern regions came under Monpa and Tibetan control.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Northwestern parts of this area came under the control of the Monpa kingdom of Monyul under Tibet which flourished between 500 BCE and 600 CE.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Monpa and Sherdukpen keep historical records of the existence of local chiefdoms in the northwest as well.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] According to Tibetan chronicles, Monyul was ruled by Gongkar Gyal, descendant of an exiled Tibetan ruler named Lhase Tsangma, the brother of Tibetan king Ralpacan who arrived in Monyul in 837 A.D or earlier.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] A descendant of Gongkar Gyal became the ruler of Trashiyangtse region of Bhutan and Gapde Tsan another descendant was the ruler of Khorwong valley in Thembang town (now West Kameng district, Arunachal Pradesh).
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Later, the second son of Gongkar Gyal, Wongme Palde who returned to Tibet owing to the poverty in Khorwong valley came back to Monyul to become its ruler.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Rgyal rigs text written in 1668 or 1728 contains a record of taxes collected.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Taxes were paid via coins, foodstuffs, or livestock from area around present-day Kameng district and Tawang district.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Monpas (Tibetan: མོན་པ) ་known to the Chinese as **Menba** were responsible for trade between Assam and Tibet and held the Koriapar Dooar at Sonitpur district of Assam.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Monpa chief were subordinate to the ruler of Tawang who in turn were subordinate to the Government of Tibet or Ganden Phodrang in Lhasa.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Tibetan government at Lhasa appointed Tibetan officials called Gellongs to supervise the local Monpa chief.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Monpa chief who looked after the Duar were called Tsorgon, a position created in the 16th century.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] According to historical Tibetan text, this region of the state of Arunachal Pradesh known as Lhoyu came under the control of Tubo Kingdom or Tibetan Empire in the 7th century CE.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The fortresses built were Dirang Dzong, Taklung Dzong and Gyangkhar Dzong to collect tax from the Dirang Monpa, Kalaktang Monpa and Tawang Monpa respectively.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The officials who collected the taxes were called Dzongpon.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The tax was carried to Tawang Monastery and then to Lhasa via Tsona city (present-day China).
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Arunachal Pradesh fell under Kham (Tibetan: ཁམས་) and Ü-Tsang (Tibetan: དབུས་གཙང་) cultural region of Tibet which also includes the Brahmaputra River watershed.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The 6th Dalai Lama Tsangyang Gyatso (1683–1706) was born in Tawang and died in Amdo (present-day China) on his way to Beijing after being kidnapped by the Mongol forces under Lha-bzang Khan, the last ruler of Khoshut Khanate on the approval of Kangxi Emperor of the Qing dynasty.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Before his death the 6th Dalai Lama instructed the construction of notable buildings like Tromzikhang in Barkhor, Lhasa.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The foothills and the plains of Arunachal Pradesh fell under the control of the Chutia kings of Assam in the medieval period.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Chutia presence in this region appears to have been strongest in the foothills, river valleys and adjoining plains of the Lohit, Dibang, Siang, Subansiri, Dikrong, Borgang and Kameng systems, rather than in the deeper interior hills.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Over time, tribal communities from the surrounding hills expanded into these sparsely occupied or abandoned plains and foothill zones.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] This process is reflected in later historical developments in eastern Arunachal Pradesh and adjoining Sadiya.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Parts of the Sadiya plains were assigned to the Mishmis, while the Namsai plains were settled by the Khamtis with the permission of the Ahom king in the mid-18th century.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] These later movements indicate that several areas which had earlier formed part of the Chutia frontier zone were gradually reoccupied by hill and trans-frontier communities after the collapse of Chutia power.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The inner hill regions of present-day Arunachal Pradesh were largely outside the direct administrative control of the valley-based kingdoms of Assam and Tibet.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] These areas were inhabited and governed by numerous tribal communities, each with its own systems of customary law, clan authority, village councils, chiefs or priestly institutions.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Political organisation varied from region to region: some communities were organised around hereditary chiefs, while others followed more decentralised village-based or clan-based systems of governance.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In the western and central parts of the state, groups such as the Nyishi, Apatani, Tagin, Galo and related Tani-speaking communities maintained their own autonomous social and political institutions.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Among several of these groups, village councils and clan elders played an important role in settling disputes, regulating land use, organising rituals and maintaining relations with neighbouring communities.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Although these societies were not usually organised as large territorial kingdoms, they controlled distinct ecological zones, trade routes and settlement clusters in the hills.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In the eastern and south-eastern parts of the state, communities such as the Adi, Mishmi, Singpho, Tangsa, Nocte and Wancho also maintained independent or semi-independent chiefdoms and village polities.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Some of these communities had closer contact with the plains of Assam, while others were connected with the hill regions of present-day Myanmar and Tibet.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Nocte and Wancho areas, for example, had hereditary chiefs, while many Adi and Mishmi groups were organised through village councils, clan heads and ritual specialists.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] These tribal communities interacted with neighbouring states through trade, tribute, warfare, diplomacy and ritual exchange.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Salt, beads, metal objects, cloth, livestock, forest products and agricultural produce moved between the hills and the plains.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The foothill passes and river valleys therefore functioned as contact zones between the tribal communities of the interior and the larger political powers of the Brahmaputra Valley, including the Chutia, Ahom and later colonial administrations.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Despite these interactions, the interior hill communities retained a high degree of autonomy.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] External states generally exercised stronger influence over the foothills, trade routes and frontier settlements than over the deeper hill regions.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The political history of Arunachal Pradesh before the colonial period was therefore not shaped by a single kingdom or centralised authority, but by a combination of frontier states, local chiefdoms, village republics, clan territories and shifting networks of exchange.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Following the annexation of Assam after the First Anglo-Burmese War, the British inherited the previous Ahom Kingdom's tributary system in appeasing the frontier tribes known as *posa*.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The system was optimised with contracts to the leading chiefs to standardise who had the right to demand tribute from the British to curb raiding.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] With the goals of economic growth and extraction of tea, coal, oil and minerals in Assam, the British set out on a policy to curb tribal headhunting, civil wars and slavery.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Prior to the Simla Conference there was no declaration of British intentions towards the frontier tracts and tribes of the region.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The region was treated as terra nullius neither to the British Raj or to any other entity.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The British in their official documentation did not assert any recognition or affiliation of the frontier tracts with Tibetan or Chinese polities.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Their assumption rested in that tribal territories were within the British sphere of influence until clear Tibetan boundaries were evident.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In the 19th century, there was uncertainty along the border and no urgency to demarcate it.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The first territorial policy with the frontier tracts was the introduction of the Inner Line system.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] This was designed to restrict people beyond a certain territory to avoid provoking hostile relations with tribal groups on the frontier.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] However, the Inner Line was less of an international boundary and more of a framework for migration management.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Before 1880, tribal relations with the British were handled *ad-hoc* by British officials.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 1880, a Frontier Tract Regulation was adopted and extended to any tract inhabited or freqeuented by barbarous or semi-civilised tribes adjoining or within the borders of any of the districts with the Territories under the administration of the Chief Commissioner of Assam.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] With this declaration, the Dibrugah Frontier Tract (east of the Subansiri River) was formally put under the administration of Lakhimpur with a political officer at Sadiya.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The western section was in charge of the Deputy Commissioner of Darrang.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 1912, the sudden activity of Chinese military forces in the vicinity prompted the British to negotiate a formal delimitation of the international boundary.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] This was attributed to the Qing Empire's attempts to establish Chinese authority in the Kham area of Tibet in 1910.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The British recorded that various reports of dubious origin stated Chinese influence in the region.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] A party of Chinese were rumoured to have appeared in the Aka country, not far from the Inner Line boundary in the west.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Chinese officials in Rima had also reportedly summoned the Mishmi chiefs to offer them to submit.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Other rumours described a Chinese force ordered to march down the Siang river valley into the homeland of the Abors.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] As a response to these rumours, the British dispatched three missions into the hills.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Miri Mission explored the hills west of the Subansiri River.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Abor Mission between Subansiri and Siang was conducted along with the Mishmi Mission in the Sisseri, Dibang and Lohit river valleys.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The goal of these missions was to establish the "natural and traditional frontier" between the frontier tribes and Tibet, and to inform the tribes that they were under British sovereignty and must adhere to British laws and punishments.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The results of these missions led the boundary commission to create the McMahon Line, which was influenced by the findings of the three missions.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The one major exception was the incorporation of Tawang in the westernmost area.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The inhabitants held close cultural and religious ties to Tibet and Bhutan, and the British had previously characterised this as a "dependancy of Thibet" not included in the tribal area designation.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Another region between the tribals and Bhutan was considered highly undesirable, which in 1914 was examined by the British.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The report by the Balipara Political Officer stated that the Tawang Monastery, the political authority of the region, was an offshoot of Drepung Monastery near Lhasa but recommend incorporation into the British regardless.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Hence with these cosniderations the current McMahon line was drawn up.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 1912–13, the British Indian government established the North-East Frontier Tracts via three divisions: the Western section, the Central and Eastern section, and the Lakhimpur tract.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 1919, they eventually came to be called the Ballipara Frontier Tract, Lakhimpur Frontier Tract and Sadiya Frontier Tract.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 1913–1914, representatives of the *de facto* independent state of Tibet and Britain met in India to define the borders of 'Outer Tibet' (with respect to China).
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] British administrator Sir Henry McMahon drew the 550 miles (890 km) McMahon Line as the border between British India and Tibet, placing Tawang and other areas within British India.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Tibetan and British representatives devised the Simla Accord including the McMahon Line, but the Chinese representatives did not concur.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Simla Accord denies other benefits to China unless it assents to the Accord.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Chinese position was that Tibet was not independent from China and could not sign treaties, so the Accord was invalid, like the Anglo-Chinese (1906) and Anglo-Russian (1907) conventions.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] British records show that the condition for the Tibetan government to accept the new border was that China must accept the Simla Convention.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] As Britain was not able to get an acceptance from China, Tibetans considered the McMahon line invalid.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In the time that China did not exercise power in Tibet, the line had no serious challenges.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 1935, a Deputy Secretary in the Foreign Department, Olaf Caroe, "discovered" that the McMahon Line was not drawn on official maps.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Survey of India published a map showing the McMahon Line as the official boundary in 1937.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 1938, two decades after the Simla Conference, the British finally published the Simla Accord as a bilateral accord and the Survey of India published a detailed map showing the McMahon Line as a border of India.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In April 1938, a small British force led by Captain G.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Lightfoot arrived in Tawang and informed the monastery that the district was now Indian territory.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Tibetan government at Lhasa protested and its authority was restored after Lightfoot's return.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 1944, Britain established administrations in the area, from Dirang Dzong in the west to Walong in the east.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Administrative control extended over the area of the Tawang tract lying south of the Sela Pass when J.P.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Mills set up an Assam Rifles post at Dirang Dzong and sent the Tibetan tax-collectors packing.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] However, no steps were taken to evict Tibet from the area north of the pass which contained Tawang town.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Tawang district remained under Tibetan authority until 1951.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Following the conclusion of British rule, India gained independence in 1947, while the People's Republic of China (PRC) was founded in 1949.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The new Chinese administration maintained the position that the McMahon Line was not valid.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In October 1947, independent Tibet wrote a note to the Government of India asking for a "return" of the territories that the British had allegedly occupied from Tibet.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Among these were listed Zayul and Walong and in direction of Pemakoe, Lonag, Lopa, Mon, Bhutan, Sikkim, Darjeeling.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] After negotiation with the Indian government, Tibet relinquished claims on these territories.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In November 1950, the PRC was poised to take over Tibet by force, and India supported Tibet.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Journalist Sudha Ramachandran argued that China claimed Tawang on behalf of Tibetans, though Tibetans did not claim Tawang as part of Tibet.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In February 1951, India sent Ralengnao Khathing of Manipur with a small escort and several hundred porters to Tawang and took control of the remainder of the Tawang tract from the Tibetans, removing the Tibetan administration.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] What is now Arunachal Pradesh was established as the North-East Frontier Agency (NEFA) in 1954.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Sino-Indian relations were cordial until 1960.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Resurgence of the border disagreement was a factor leading to the Sino-Indian War in 1962, during which China captured most of Arunachal Pradesh, including the Tawang tract.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] China soon declared victory, withdrew back to the McMahon Line, and returned Indian prisoners of war in 1963.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The war resulted in the termination of barter trade with Tibet, although since 2007 the Indian government has shown signs of wanting to resume barter trade.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Under the leadership of Indira Gandhi, The North-East Frontier Agency (NEFA) was renamed Arunachal Pradesh by Bibhabasu Das Shastri, Daya Krishna Goswami and O.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Upadhya on 20 January 1972, and it became a union territory.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Later on, Arunachal Pradesh became a state on 20 February 1987 during Rajiv Gandhi's government.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] NB: K A A Raja, as Chief Commissioner to NEFA, under Assam, whose Capital used to be Shillong, later on went to become the first Lieutenant Governor to the Union Territory of Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The 14th Dalai Lama did not originally recognise India's sovereignty over Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] As late as 2003, he said that "Arunachal Pradesh was actually part of Tibet".
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In January 2007, the Dalai Lama said that both Britain and Tibet had recognised the McMahon Line in 1914.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 2008, he said that Arunachal Pradesh was a part of India under the agreement signed by Tibetan and British representatives.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] According to the Dalai Lama, "In 1962 during the India-China war, the People's Liberation Army (PLA) occupied all these areas (Arunachal Pradesh) but they announced a unilateral ceasefire and withdrew, accepting the current international boundary".
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In recent years, China has occasionally asserted its claims on Tawang.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] India rebutted these claims and told the Chinese government that Tawang is an integral part of India.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] India reiterated this to China when the two prime ministers met in Thailand in October 2009.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] A report that the Chinese Army had briefly invaded Arunachal Pradesh in 2016 was denied by India's Minister of State for Home Affairs, Kiren Rijiju.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In April 2017, China strongly objected to a visit to Tawang by the Dalai Lama, as it had to an earlier visit by the US ambassador.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] China had objected to the Dalai Lama's previous visits to the area.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 2024, *The New York Times* reported that, according to satellite imagery, China had constructed villages along and inside of disputed territory within Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Chinese individuals, called "border guardians", received annual subsidies to relocate to newly built villages and paid to conduct border patrols.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Arunachal Pradesh has faced threats from insurgent groups, notably the National Socialist Council of Nagaland (NSCN), who are believed to have base camps in the districts of Changlang and Tirap.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] These groups seek to decrease the influence of Indian government in the region and merge part of Arunachal Pradesh into Nagaland.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Indian army is present along the Tibetan border to thwart any Chinese incursion.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Under the Foreigners (Protected Areas) Order 1958 (India), Inner Line Permits (ILPs) are required to enter Arunachal Pradesh through any of its checkgates on the border with Assam.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Arunachal Pradesh is located between 26.28° N and 29.30° N latitude and 91.20° E and 97.30° E longitude and has an area of 83,743 km2 (32,333 sq mi).
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The highest peak in the state is Kangto, at 7,060 metres (23,160 ft).
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Nyegi Kangsang, the main Gorichen peak, and the Eastern Gorichen peak are other tall Himalaya peaks.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The state's mountain ranges, in the extreme East of India, are described as "the place where the sun rises" in historical Indian texts and named the Aruna Mountains, which inspired the name of the state.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The villages of Dong (more accessible by car, and with a lookout favoured by tourists) and Vijaynagar (on the edge of Myanmar) receive the first sunlight in all of India.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Major rivers of Arunachal Pradesh include the Kameng, Subansiri, Siang (Brahmaputra), Dibang, Lohit and Noa Dihing rivers.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Subsurface flows and summer snow melt contribute to the volume of water.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Mountains until the Siang river are classified as the Eastern Himalayas.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Those between the Siang and Noa Dihing are classified as the Mishmi Hills that may be part of the Hengduan Mountains.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Mountains south of the Noa Dihing in Tirap and Longding districts are part of the Patkai Range.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The climate of Arunachal Pradesh varies with elevation.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The low-altitude areas have a humid subtropical climate.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] High-altitude areas (3,500–5,500 m) have a subtropical highland climate and alpine climate.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Arunachal Pradesh receives 2,000 to 5,000 millimetres (79 to 197 in) of rainfall annually, 70%–80% obtained between May and October.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Arunachal Pradesh has among the highest diversity of mammals and birds in India.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] There are around 750 species of birds and more than 200 species of mammals in the state.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Arunachal's forests account for one-third of habitat area within the Himalayan biodiversity hot-spot.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 2013, 31,273 km2 (12,075 sq mi) of Arunachal's forests were identified as part of a vast area of continuous forests (65,730 km2 or 25,380 sq mi, including forests in Myanmar, China and Bhutan) known as Intact forest landscapes.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] There are three tiger reserves in the state: a reserve in Namdapha National Park, Mouling National Park and Pakke Tiger Reserve.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In the year 2000, Arunachal Pradesh was covered with 63,093 km2 (24,360 sq mi) of tree cover (77% of its land area).
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] At the lowest elevations, essentially at Arunachal Pradesh's border with Assam, are Brahmaputra Valley semi-evergreen forests.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Much of the state, including the Himalayan foothills and the Patkai hills, are home to Eastern Himalayan broadleaf forests.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Toward the northern border with Tibet, with increasing elevation, come a mixture of Eastern and Northeastern Himalayan subalpine conifer forests followed by Eastern Himalayan alpine shrub and meadows and ultimately rock and ice on the highest peaks.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] It supports many medicinal plants and within Ziro valley of Lower Subansiri district 158 medicinal plants are being used by its inhabitants.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The mountain slopes and hills are covered with alpine, temperate, and subtropical forests of dwarf rhododendron, oak, pine, maple and fir.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The state has Mouling and Namdapha national parks.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The major animal species are tiger, leopard, snow leopard, Asian elephant, sambar deer, chital deer, barking deer, sloth bear, mithun (*Bos frontalis*), gaur, dhole, giant squirrel, marbled cat, leopard cat.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] A new subspecies of hoolock gibbon has been described from the state which has been named as the Mishmi Hills hoolock gibbon (*H. h. mishmiensis*).
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Three new giant flying squirrels were also described from the state during the last one and half-decade.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] These were, Mechuka giant flying squirrel, Mishmi Hills giant flying squirrel, and Mebo giant flying squirrel.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Arunachal Pradesh comprises three divisions, namely, Central, East and West, each headed by a divisional commissioner and twenty-eight districts, each administered by a deputy commissioner.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] West Siang is the largest district by area and Tawang is the smallest district.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Papum is the largest district by population and Diwang Valley is the smallest.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Below are the major towns in Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] As per the 2011 Census, Arunachal Pradesh has 12 Scheduled Tribes, comprising 68.79% of its population.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In between there are transition zones, such as the Aka/Hruso/Miji/Sherdukpen area, between the Tibetan Buddhist tribes and the animist Tani hill tribes.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In addition, there are isolated peoples scattered throughout the state, such as the Sulung.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Within each of these cultural spheres, one finds populations of related tribes speaking related languages and sharing similar traditions.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In the Tibetic area, one finds large numbers of Monpa tribespeople, with several subtribes speaking closely related but mutually incomprehensible languages, and also large numbers of Tibetan refugees.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Within the Tani area, major tribes include the Nyishi.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Apatani also live among the Nyishi, but are distinct.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In the centre, one finds predominantly Galo people, with the major sub-groups of Karka, Lodu, Bogum, Lare and Pugo among others, extending to the Ramo and Pailibo areas (which are close in many ways to Galo).
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In the east, one finds the Adi with many subtribes including Padam, Pasi, Minyong and Bokar, among others.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Milang, while also falling within the general Adi sphere, are in many ways quite distinct.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Moving east, the Idu, Miju and Digaru make up the Mishmi cultural-linguistic area.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Moving southeast, the Tai Khamti are linguistically distinct from their neighbours and culturally distinct from the majority of other Arunachalese tribes.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] They follow the Theravada sect of Buddhism.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] They also exhibit considerable convergence with the Singpho and Tangsa Naga tribes of the same area, all of which are also found in Burma.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] They are one of the most recent people group migrated to Arunachal region from Burma.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Nocte Naga and Wancho Naga are another two major ethnic tribes.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Both the tribes exhibit very much cultural similarities.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Finally, the Deori tribe is also a major community in the state, with their own distinctive identity.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] They are the descendants of the priestly class of Chutia people who were allowed to continue their livelihood after the defeat of the Chutias.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Deoris are one of the only Arunachal tribes in the historical records – which shows they are among the first ethnic groups to inhabit the Himalayas of the districts of Dibang Valley and Lohit, before the arrival of many other tribes in the region between 1600 and 1900.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] However, the religious landscape of Arunachal Pradesh is diverse with no single religious group representing the majority of the population, although it is one of the few Indian states where Christianity has the most followers.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] A small number of Arunachali people have traditionally identified as Hindus, although the number may grow as animist traditions are absorbed into Hinduism.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Tibetan Buddhism predominates in the districts of Tawang, West Kameng, and isolated regions adjacent to Tibet.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Theravada Buddhism is practised by groups living near the Myanmar border.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Around 30% of the population are Christians.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Buddhism arrived in Arunachal Pradesh in the 8th century CE from Tibet.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 1971, the percentage of Christians in the state was 0.79%.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] This increased to 10.3% by 1991 and by 2011 it had crossed 25%.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The vast majority of Arunachal Pradesh speaks Tani languages of the Tibeto-Burman language family.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Tani people are indigenous to central Arunachal Pradesh, including (moving from west to east) the Nyishi, the Apatani, the Tagin, the Galo, the Bokar, the Adi, the Padam, the Pasi, and the Minyong.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The Tani languages are noticeably characterised by an overall relative uniformity, suggesting relatively recent origin and dispersal within their present-day area of concentration.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Most of the Tani languages are mutually intelligible with at least one other Tani language, meaning that the area constitutes a dialect chain, as was once found in much of Europe; only Apatani and Milang stand out as relatively unusual in the Tani context.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Tani languages are among the better-studied languages of the region.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] To the east of the Tani area lie three virtually undescribed and highly endangered languages of the "Mishmi" group of Tibeto-Burman: Idu, Digaru and Mishmi people.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] A number of speakers of these languages are also found in Tibet.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The relationships of these languages, both among one another and to other area languages, are as yet uncertain.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Further south, one finds the Singpho (Kachin) language, which is primarily spoken by large populations in Myanmar's Kachin State, and the Nocte and Wancho languages, which show affiliations to certain Naga languages spoken to the south in modern-day Nagaland.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] To the west and north of the Tani area are found at least one and possibly as many as four Bodic languages, including Dakpa and Tshangla language; within modern-day India, these languages go by the cognate but, in usage, distinct designations Monpa and Memba.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Most speakers of these languages or closely related Bodic languages are found in neighbouring Bhutan and Tibet, and Monpa and Memba populations remain closely adjacent to these border regions.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Among them are Sherdukpen, Bugun, Hruso, Koro, Miji, Bangru and Puroik/Sulung.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The high linguistic significance these languages is belied by the extreme paucity of documentation and description of them, even in view of their highly endangered status.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Finally, other than the Bodic and Tani groups, there are also certain migratory languages that are largely spoken by migratory and central government employees serving in the state in different departments and institutions in modern-day Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] They are classified as Non-Tribal as per the provisions of the Constitution of India.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Outside of Tibeto-Burman, one finds in Arunachal Pradesh a single representative of the Tai family, spoken by Tai Khamti, which is closely affiliated to the Shan language of Myanmar's Shan State.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Seemingly, Khampti is a recent arrival in Arunachal Pradesh whose presence dates to 18th or early 19th-century migrations from northern Myanmar.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In addition to English, various Indo-Aryan languages Assamese, Bengali, Nepali and especially Hindi are making strong inroads into Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Primarily as a result of the primary education system—in which classes are generally taught by Hindi-speaking migrant teachers from Bihar and other Hindi-speaking parts of northern India, a large and growing section of the population now speaks a semi-creolised variety of Hindi as a mother tongue.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Hindi acts as a lingua franca for most of the people in the state.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Despite, or perhaps because of, the linguistic diversity of the region, English is the only official language recognised in the state.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Literacy has risen in official figures to 66.95% in 2011 from 54.74% in 2001.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The literate population is said to number 789,943.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The chart below displays the trend of the gross state domestic product of Arunachal Pradesh at market prices by the Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation with figures in billions of Indian Rupees.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Arunachal Pradesh's gross state domestic product was estimated at US$706 million at current prices in 2004 and US$1.75 billion at current prices in 2012.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Agriculture primarily drives the economy.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Jhum, the local term used for shifting cultivation is being widely practised among the tribal groups, though owing to the gradual growth of other sources of income in the recent years, it is not being practised as prominently as it was earlier.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Arunachal Pradesh has close to 61,000 km2 of forests, and forest products are the next most significant sector of the economy.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Among the crops grown here are rice, maize, millet, wheat, pulses, sugarcane, ginger, and oilseeds.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Arunachal is also ideal for horticulture and fruit orchards.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Its major industries are rice mills, fruit preservation and processing units, and handloom handicrafts.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Sawmills and plywood trades are prohibited under law.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] A significant portion of India's unexplored hydroelectric capacity is attributed to Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 2008, the Arunachal Pradesh government entered into several memoranda of understanding with multiple companies, outlining around 42 hydroelectric projects intended to generate over 27,000 MW of electricity.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Construction of the Upper Siang Hydroelectric Project, which is expected to generate between 10,000 and 12,000 MW, began in April 2009.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Itanagar Airport, a greenfield project serving Itanagar, was constructed at Holongi at a cost of ₹6.5 billion.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 2022, IndiGo began direct flights to Itanagar from Mumbai and Kolkata.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Alliance Air operates flights to the state flying from Kolkata via Guwahati to Pasighat Airport.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] This route commenced in May 2018 under the Government's Regional Connectivity Scheme UDAN following the completion of a passenger terminal at Pasighat Airport in 2017.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] State-owned Daporijo Airport, Ziro Airport, Along Airport, and Tezu Airport are small and not in operation, but the government has proposed to develop them.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Before the state was connected by roads, these airstrips were used to distribute food.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The main highway of Arunachal Pradesh is the Trans-Arunachal Highway, National Highway 13 (1,293 km (803 mi); formerly NH-229 and NH-52).
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] It originates in Tawang and spans most of the width of Arunachal Pradesh, then crosses south into Assam and ends at Wakro.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The project was announced by then Prime Minister Manmohan Singh in 2008 for completion by 2015–16, but only became operational in 2018.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] NH-15 through Assam follows the southern border of Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Access to central Arunachal Pradesh has been facilitated by the Bogibeel Bridge, an earthquake-resistant rail and road bridge over the Brahmaputra River in Assam, opened for public use on 25 December 2018 by Prime Minister Narendra Modi.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] A spur highway numbered NH-415 services Itanagar.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] State-owned Arunachal Pradesh State Transport Services (APSTS) runs daily bus service from Itanagar to most district headquarters including Tezpur, Guwahati in Assam, Shillong in Meghalaya, and Dimapur in Nagaland.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] As of 2007, every village is connected by road, thanks to funding provided by the central government.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Every small town has its own bus station with daily bus service.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Connections to Assam have increased commerce.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In 2014, two additional east–west highways were proposed: an Industrial Corridor Highway in the lower foothills, and a Frontier Highway along the McMahon Line.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The proposed alignment of the Frontier Highway has been published.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Arunachal Pradesh got its first railway line in late 2013 with the opening of the new link line from Harmuti on the main Rangpara North–Murkongselak railway line to Naharlagun in Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The construction of the 33-kilometre 5 ft 6 in (1,676 mm) broad-gauge railway line was completed in 2012, and the link became operational after the gauge conversion of the main line from Assam.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The state capital Itanagar was added to the Indian railway map on 12 April 2014 via the newly built 20-kilometre Harmuti-Naharlagun railway line, when a train from Dekargaon in Assam reached Naharlagun railway station, 10 kilometres from the centre of Itanagar, a total distance of 181 kilometres.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] On 20 February 2015, the first through train was run from New Delhi to Naharlagun, flagged off from the capital by the Indian prime minister, Narendra Modi.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] India plans to eventually extend the railway to Tawang, near the border with China.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The state government is expanding the relatively underdeveloped education system with the assistance of NGOs like Vivekananda Kendra, leading to a sharp improvement in the state's literacy rate.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The first college, Jawaharlal Nehru College, Pasighat, was established in 1964.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The First Technical University is Established in 2014 namely North East Frontier Technical University (NEFTU).
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] In Aalo, West Siang District by The Automobile Society India, New Delhi.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] There is also a deemed university, the North Eastern Regional Institute of Science and Technology as well as the National Institute of Technology, Arunachal Pradesh, established on 18 August 2010, is located in Yupia (headquarter of Itanagar).
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] NERIST plays an important role in technical and management higher education.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The directorate of technical education conducts examinations yearly so that students who qualify can continue on to higher studies in other states.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Of the above institutions, only the following institutions are accredited by NAAC (National Assessment and Accreditation Council), in the order of their grade: Jawaharlal Nehru College, Pasighat (Grade A), St Claret College, Ziro (Grade A), Indira Gandhi Govt.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] College, Tezu (Grade B++), Rajiv Gandhi University (Grade B), National Institute of Technology, Arunachal Pradesh (Grade B), Dera Natung Government College, Itanagar (Grade B), Govt.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] College, Bomdila (Grade B), Donyi Polo Govt.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] College, Kamki (Grade B), and Rang Frah Govt.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Wangcha Rajkumar Government College, Deomali is the only college in the southeastern part of Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] It caters to the students from Tirap, Changlang and Longding districts.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] There are also trust institutes, like Pali Vidyapith, run by Buddhists.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] They teach Pali and Khamti scripts in addition to typical education subjects.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Khamti is the only tribe in Arunachal Pradesh that has its own script.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] Libraries of scriptures are in a number of places in Lohit district, the largest one being in Chowkham.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The state has two polytechnic institutes: Rajiv Gandhi Government Polytechnic in Itanagar established in 2002 and Tomi Polytechnic College in Basar established in 2006.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] There are two law colleges, namely, the private-owned Arunachal Law Academy at Itanagar and the government-owned Jarbom Gamlin Government Law College at Jote, Itanagar.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p01] The College of Horticulture and Forestry is affiliated to the Central Agricultural University, Imphal.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] Arunachal Pradesh suffered political crisis between April 2016 and December 2016.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] The Indian National Congress Chief Minister Nabam Tuki replaced Jarbom Gamlin as the Chief Minister of Arunachal Pradesh on 1 November 2011 and continued until January 2016.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] After a political crisis in 2016, President's rule was imposed ending his tenure as the chief minister.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] In February 2016, Kalikho Pul became the Chief Minister when 14 disqualified MLAs were reinstated by the Supreme Court.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] On 13 July 2016, the Supreme Court quashed the Arunachal Pradesh Governor J.P.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] Rajkhowa's order to advance the Assembly session from 14 January 2016 to 16 December 2015, which resulted in President's rule in Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] As a result, Nabam Tuki was reinstated as the Chief Minister of Arunachal Pradesh on 13 July 2016.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] But hours before floor test, he resigned as the chief minister on 16 July 2016.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] He was succeeded by Pema Khandu as the INC Chief Minister who later joined PPA in September 2016 along with majority of MLAs.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] Pema Khandu further joined BJP in December 2016 along with majority of MLAs.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] Arunachal Pradesh becomes second northeast Indian state to achieve ODF status.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] During 2017, 2021, and 2023, China compiled a list of name alterations for multiple locations in Arunachal Pradesh, in both Chinese and Tibetan languages.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] China asserts these areas as belonging to "Southern Tibet" and being integral parts of China.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] The proposed changes encompassed 11 alterations, covering geographical landmarks like mountain summits and rivers, as well as residential zones.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] The Indian government has continued to reject Chinese claims of geographical ownership of parts of Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] National military forces on both sides have increased over the Indian-Chinese border.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] On 28 August 2023, China further provoked India when the PRC's Ministry of Natural Resources released its new 'standard map' in which Arunachal Pradesh was depicted as a part of PRC.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] Other internationally disputed lands and waters were also depicted as PRC territory on their new map.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] Arunachal Pradesh Khaw Tai (Khamti Rice) was awarded the Geographical Indication (GI) status tag from the Geographical Indications Registry, under the Union Government of India, on 3 October 2023 and is valid until 12 December 2031.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] Namsai Organic Spices and Agricultural Producer Company Limited from Lohit, proposed the GI registration of Arunachal Pradesh Khaw Tai (Khamti Rice).
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] After filing the application in December 2021, the rice was granted the GI tag in 2023 by the Geographical Indication Registry in Chennai, making the name "Arunachal Pradesh Khaw Tai (Khamti Rice)" exclusive to the rice grown in the region.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] It thus became the first rice variety from Arunachal Pradesh and the 3rd type of goods from Arunachal Pradesh to earn the GI tag.
[src:ara-drink/arunachal-pradesh-p02] The GI tag protects the rice from illegal selling and marketing, and gives it legal protection and a unique identity.
